# Fashion Nova Case Study — Project Notes

## Project Title
Does Hyper-Influencer Marketing Build Customer Loyalty or a Revolving Door?
A Retail Strategy Case Study — Fashion Nova (2015-2022)

## Hypothesis
Fashion Nova's synchronized influencer campaign spikes drive short-term 
revenue surges but are followed by declining customer sentiment and 
increasing complaint volumes — indicating an acquisition-over-loyalty model.

## Key Data Sources
- Google Trends: Fashion Nova 2015-2022 (USA, Shopping category)
- Trustpilot: Customer sentiment over time
- Press/public reports: Revenue estimates
- Wikipedia + public press: Campaign timeline

---

## Findings So Far

### 1. Google Trends Analysis
- 17 spikes identified between 2015-2022
- Clear upward trend 2016-2018, downward after
- Peak: November 2018
- Seasonal pattern every year:
  - Nov spike = Black Friday/Thanksgiving
  - Feb/Mar spike = Valentine's Day promotions
  - May/Jun spike = Summer collection + influencer drops
  - July = consistently lowest month every year
- July lows deepening in 2020, 2021, 2022 despite continued 
  influencer spend = diminishing returns signal
- Interpretation: Customers not returning between campaigns

### 2. Revenue & Business Data
- #1 most-searched fashion brand on Google in 2018 (peak confirmed)
- Spent $40 million on influencer partnerships in 2019 alone
- Generated $111.9 million in Earned Media Value from influencer 
  collaborations in 2019
- Current annual revenue: ~$941.6M to $1B+ (estimated, private company)
- Revenue held up only because influencer spend kept increasing
- Growth has stalled despite continued spend

### 3. App Engagement (Loyalty Proxy)
- App downloads peaked: March 2021 at 390,000
- App downloads by Feb 2025: ~250,000
- Decline: 36% drop in app engagement
- Interpretation: Customer acquisition still working but retention 
  is declining — supports revolving door hypothesis

